It is Irish Heritage Month and throughout this month I am going to be exploring Irish-Canadian heritage.
Today, it is the story of Griffintown. It was once a thriving Irish neighbourhood in Montreal that was mostly demolished in the 1960s.
Let's learn more!

üßµ1/7

First appearing in the 1820s in Montreal, Griffintown was named for Mary Griffin, who had the land subdivided with streets in 1804.
Irish labourers working on the Lachine Canal began to settle there in the early 19th century. The Irish also built the Victoria Bridge.

üßµ2/7

The community was centered around St. Ann's Catholic Church, which opened in 1854. The neighbourhood was a thriving place for decades.
By the 20th century, immigrants from Italy, Ukraine and France started to change the demographics of the neighbourhood. 

üßµ3/7

Throughout the mid-part of the 20th century, The Griff as it was called began to depopulate due to changing times. The CNR built elevated tracks through the area and the Lachine Canals importance was decreased by the Saint Lawrence Seaway in 1959.

üßµ4/7

In 1962, Griffintown was rezoned and many buildings were demolished in the 1960s to make way for the Bonaventure Expressway.
There were claims that it was demolished due to Expo 67 and the feeling the area was unsightly to visitors.

üßµ5/7

By the 1990s, there was little left of the historic architecture of Griffintown. Today, there are plans in place to redevelop Griffintown from industrial to a high-density neighbourhood with condo towers. This redevelopment is expected to finished in 2025.

üßµ6/7

An issue that's been bothering me in recent months is just how hard it is to tell major actors, "we will punish you for doing the wrong thing and reward you for doing the right thing." Or rather: how little attention there seems to be to toward solving the coordination problem at its root.

Right now, large-scale action against some actor mostly means trying to inflict damage on its reputation. With an extremely decentralized model of activism, that might be the only way you can get the average citizen to participate: put out very loud signals about who's Bad and hope people catch on.

But that works very slowly; it can't contain much nuance; it isn't predictable what messages will stick. No one (save state actors) is able to tell a company, "We're not saying you're bad because you did this in the past, but it still needs to stop."

And it's even harder to say, "You've done more or less what we asked so we're cool now". Protests might (*might*) stop, but they were probably going to fizzle out anyway. It's often better to hope for that than risk the reputational damage from the *other* side.

Worse yet is when the actor is something that generally only does business with other corporate entities, like, I don't know, a law firm. Maybe here it works in our favor that the few individuals who *do* interact with them directly are going to be much more high-information.

That is: the reputational damage happens (where it matters) without any large-scale campaigns. Or, maybe it means that the people in question are more conscious about focusing on their (company's) interest (if they're on our side at all).

So there's another part of the coordination problem: figuring out where to strategically put pressure in order to *indirectly* influence an actor. That probably means a lot of work that will only pay off if the other parts of the coordination problem have been solved.

As I see it, unions‚Äîfairly active ones at least‚Äîare the model for solving this kind of coordination problem: loosely hierarchical, with full-time staff able to focus on these details at higher levels and a need to develop relationships of trust between levels:

in particular a rank-and-file who largely know they can trust their reps because they've had their backs before. 

I don't know how many contemporary unions are active at that level, but regardless not very many Americans are in unions of any kind. So we're left where we are.
